Car Review Template — automore.com.au
Purpose: Structured prompt template for generating credible, experience-backed car reviews that rank in 2026 Google. Designed for AI generation but with mandatory human/data inputs that signal genuine experience. Never use SEO-framework acronyms (e.g. E-E-A-T, YMYL) in titles, body copy, author bios, or meta text — readers should see plain-language editorial standards only.

INPUT VARIABLES (fill before generation)
yamlmake: 
model: 
variant:           # e.g. "GXL 4x4 Auto"
year_range:        # e.g. "2018-2023" for a generation review, or single year for new
body_style:        # SUV / sedan / ute / hatch / wagon / 4WD
price_range_aud:   # current AU market range
fuel_type:         # petrol / diesel / hybrid / PHEV / EV
drive_type:        # FWD / RWD / AWD / 4WD
target_buyer:      # e.g. "tradies needing dual-cab work ute", "growing family"
review_angle:      # NEW: "Should you buy in 2026?" / USED: "Is it worth it second-hand?"
location_context:  # AU-specific: WA / nationwide / Outback / urban
key_competitors:   # 2-3 direct rivals
real_world_data:   # mandatory: at least 3 of {fuel test, towing test, owner survey, mechanic input, long drive notes}

REVIEW STRUCTURE
1. Title (H1)
Format: [Year/Range] [Make] [Model] [Variant] Review: [Specific Verdict Hook]
Examples:

2018-2023 Toyota Hilux SR5 Review: Still the Tradie Benchmark, or Time for a Rival?
2024 BYD Atto 3 Review: The EV That Actually Makes Sense for Australian Families

Rules: Specific year/range. Avoid "ultimate guide" / "best." Verdict should be a real question or claim, not generic.
2. Lede (50-80 words, no H2)
Open with one specific observation a real driver would make in the first hour. Not a feature list. Not a brochure quote.
Good: "After 600km from Perth to Esperance in the Hilux SR5, two things were obvious: the seats are still better than they have any right to be at this price, and the 2.8L diesel still drinks more than Toyota's claim suggests — 9.1L/100km on the highway, not the 7.9 they advertise."
Bad: "The Toyota Hilux is a popular ute that has been on sale in Australia for many years."
3. Verdict Box (above-the-fold)
THE QUICK VERDICT
Rating: [X/10]
Best for: [specific buyer in one line]
Skip if: [specific buyer in one line]
Price as tested: $[X] drive-away ([state])
Real-world fuel: [X]L/100km (vs [X] claimed)
4. What We Actually Did (H2: "How We Tested This [Model]")
This is the primary experience-and-methodology anchor section. Critical.
State explicitly:

How long the car was driven (km / days / weeks)
What conditions (highway / city / off-road / towing / loaded)
What was measured (fuel, 0-100, payload, etc.)
Who drove it (name + relevant background — mechanic, long-term owner, tradie, etc.)
When (month/year — recency matters for Google)

Even short — "We had this Hilux for 4 days and 740km, including a 200km dirt section near Wave Rock and a loaded run with 600kg of timber" — this single paragraph does more for credibility than 2,000 words of generic prose.
5. What's New / What's Changed (H2)
Only relevant for: new model years, facelifts, generation reviews.

Bullet the actual changes vs the previous year/gen
Flag what's marketing fluff vs what's a real change
100-150 words max

6. Driving It (H2: "What It's Like to Drive")
Sub-sections (H3) — pick 3-4 that match the car:

Around town
On the highway
Loaded / towing (utes, large SUVs)
Off-road (4WDs only)
Twisty roads (performance/sporty cars)
Charging and range (EVs/PHEVs only)

Each H3: 100-200 words. Specific observations. Numbers where possible. Compare to a named competitor.
Forbidden phrases: "planted feel," "engaging dynamics," "premium feel," "refined ride." These are AI tells. Replace with concrete observations: "Body roll is noticeable through Reabold Hill's roundabouts but the car settles quickly."
7. Inside the Cabin (H2)
Cover, in this order:

Front seat comfort (specific — bolster, lumbar, long-drive verdict)
Driving position (visibility, wheel reach, dash height for shorter drivers)
Tech (infotainment lag, CarPlay/Android Auto stability, voice control)
Storage (real measurements — does a 1.5L bottle fit in the door? phone tray?)
Back seat (legroom for a 6ft adult behind a 6ft driver, ISOFIX count, air vents)
Boot (litres claimed vs what fits — a real test like "two large suitcases plus a pram")

8. Fuel / Range / Running Costs (H2)
Mandatory for ranking on commercial intent queries:

Real-world fuel consumption (your test, not WLTP)
Service intervals + capped pricing (5-year cost where available)
Insurance band / typical premium for a 35yo in Perth
Tyre size + replacement cost
For EVs: real-world range, charging speeds tested, time to 80% on DC fast

9. Safety (H2)

ANCAP rating + year of test (state both — older ratings are worth less)
Active safety features list
One or two real observations: "AEB triggered once unnecessarily on a quiet street; lane-keep is gentle and not annoying"

10. Reliability and Common Issues (H2)
Critical for used-car reviews. This is where most AI reviews fail and where you can win:

Known issues by year/variant (cite specific TSBs, recalls, or owner complaints)
Service history red flags to look for
Mechanic perspective: what fails, what costs to fix
Resale value trend (3-year and 5-year)

For your site specifically: this is where partnering with the mechanic (even remotely, via a quote per review) gives you a genuine differentiator no AI competitor has.
11. The Competition (H2)
Three named rivals. For each:

One-line "why pick this over the [model]"
One-line "why pick the [model] over this"
Price comparison (drive-away)

12. Who Should Buy It (H2)
Two short lists, very specific:

Buy this if: 4-5 specific buyer scenarios
Look elsewhere if: 3-4 specific dealbreakers

Avoid generic ("if you want a reliable car"). Be concrete ("if you do 80%+ highway driving in WA and want under 8L/100km").
13. Final Verdict (H2)

Rating with breakdown (Performance / Comfort / Practicality / Value / Reliability — each /10)
One paragraph summary (60-80 words) that someone could screenshot and share
A single clear recommendation

14. FAQ (H2)
Mandatory for SERP features. 5-7 questions. Pull from:

"People also ask" on Google for [make] [model] review
Real questions from Aussie owner forums (Whirlpool, OzBargain, model-specific FB groups)

Format:
**Is the [model] reliable?**
[40-60 word answer with a specific data point]

**How much does a [model] cost to service?**
[Real numbers]
Common queries to cover: reliability, common problems, fuel economy, towing capacity (if applicable), best year to buy, vs [biggest competitor].
15. About the Reviewer / Author Box (mandatory)
This is the second trust anchor (who tested, when, how sourced). Do not skip.
ABOUT THIS REVIEW
Reviewed by: [Name]
Background: [1-2 sentence credential — "Owns and operates [shop], 20+ years on Toyota diesels" or "Has driven 14 utes commercially across WA mining sites"]
Test conducted: [Month Year]
Test vehicle source: [Privately owned / Manufacturer loan / Dealer test drive / Workshop customer]
Disclosures: [any relationships]

PRE-PUBLISH EDITORIAL CHECKLIST (run before publish)
The MCP should verify each is true before flagging the article ready:

 At least one specific number that's not from the brochure (real fuel, real 0-100, real boot test)
 At least one named location in Australia (a road, suburb, or region)
 At least one direct comparison to a specific named competitor
 At least one negative observation (no review is all positive — Google distrusts these)
 At least one mechanic/long-term-owner data point for used reviews
 Author name + credential present
 Test methodology stated
 Date of test stated (not just "2026")
 FAQ has at least 5 questions matching real PAA queries
 No banned phrases ("planted feel," "premium feel," "ultimate guide," "in this article we'll explore")
 First-person plural OR first-person singular consistent throughout
 At least 3 internal links to other reviews on the site (build a hub structure)
 Schema markup: Review + Vehicle + FAQPage


